t has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Glover was born in 1250, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Wilford Glover, was 20 and his mother, Glover, was 19. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Agnes Foulthures. He died in 1300, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1250–1300":"1250–1300","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1270–1291":"1270–1291","1278–1309":"1278–1309","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1232–Female":"1232–Surnud","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dunster Castle, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gnosall Heath, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England","Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gnosall, Stafford Borough, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1300":"1250–1300","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1270–1291":"1270–1291","1278–1309":"1278–1309","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1232–Female":"1232–Kuollut","1278":"1278","1300":"1300